it/conversation-ledger/known-secrets.json` (local, git-invisible, beside the allowlist); capture-time redaction then exact-matches those values out of every future draft under a `known-secret` rule id. Only `--pattern` feeds it (`--all` blanks whole content); sub-8-char values dropped. Enabled globally on this machine via `~/.config/cledger/config.json`.\n\n**Decisions (so the next agent doesn't re-litigate):**\n- The roadmap's original \"make capture-tier a strict superset of scan-tier\" framing was considered and **rejected** — promoting the deliberately-noisy scan rules to run at capture would silently rewrite innocent text, breaking the near-zero-false-positive invariant. The value-based learning above is the intended narrow form.\n- Store holds plaintext by necessity (fingerprints are one-way, can't drive exact matching); acceptable because `.git/` is as local-and-unshared as the transcripts, per the transport trust boundary.\n\n**Deferred, roughly by urgency:**\n1. Tighten the `keyword-assignment` scan rule — it fires on source identifiers (`secret: string`, `password:` keys); surfaced by dogfooding, this is what's producing most of this repo's ~93 benign findings.\n2. `chmod 0600` on known-secrets.json — near-free hardening now that the store exists.\n3. Encrypt known-secrets at rest (OS keychain; non-interactive decrypt required since capture is silent).\n4. Post-push purge, re-anchor, path-based capture exclusion, auto-renormalize, harness-artifact capture, sub-turn citation anchors.\n\n**Dogfooding note:** this repo captures its own sessions. The ledger currently has ~93 benign scan findings (our own test fixtures like `password=supersecret123`), so the ledger push is held back by default while code pushes fine. Sharing this session's ledger would require resolving those (mostly `cledger allow`).\n\nRelated: [[project-ledger-ecosystem]]\n","replaceAll":false,"structuredPatch":[{"lines":["   node_type: memory","   type: project","   originSessionId: 48648da