{"actor":{"display":"Evin Tunador","id":"evintunador@gmail.com","type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"<task-notification>\n<task-id>a96e6e1ccd9c26d11</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01HPMEg3vabFCEET6A2yvQ5V</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-evintunador-repos-evintunador-conversation-ledger/4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3/tasks/a96e6e1ccd9c26d11.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Summarize docs and roadmap\" finished</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent stops with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result># Report: conversation-ledger docs review\n\nSources read: `/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/README.md`, `/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md`, `/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md`\n\n---\n\n## 1. Product intent and core guarantees\n\n**README intro:** \"Durable, attributable records of visible coding-agent conversations, stored in your repository as git notes.\" It \"appends immutable JSONL evidence events to `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`, anchored to the commit you were on when the conversation happened. Records ride the commit DAG — merge a branch and its conversations come along — never touch your working tree or `git status`.\" And: \"The ledger itself never summarizes, ranks, or interprets. It stores what was visibly said, by whom, against which commit — nothing more.\"\n\n**PRODUCT_INTENT.md \"Purpose\":** \"Conversation Ledger preserves durable, inspectable records of visible conversations between people and coding agents. It is a general conversation provenance primitive, not an intent-analysis product. Downstream consumers may use its records as evidence about why a repository changed, but the ledger must not impose that interpretation.\" The record must remain useful beyond a single tool: \"cross-CLI continuity, archival/export, code attribution, review, and later intent retrieval are all valid independent uses.\"\n\n**\"Auditable history\" here means:**\n- Events are immutable and content-addressed: `id` is `ev1-` + sha256 of the identity subset, so \"capture is idempotent by construction, and the id doubles as the content hash that makes mutation detectable\" (TECHNICAL_DESIGN, \"Canonical objects\").\n- \"Redaction appends a `redaction` event rather than silently rewriting history\" (README, \"Storage model\"); TECHNICAL_DESIGN calls this \"honest history without secret retention.\"\n- Behavioral commitments (PRODUCT_INTENT): \"Preserve source material and provenance; do not silently rewrite history\"; \"Preserve exact visible turns before creating optional derived views\"; record \"repository, branch, commit, worktree state, author, timestamps, and capture mechanism with each artifact whenever available\"; \"Keep storage out of ordinary working-tree status views while retaining normal Git durability and shareability\"; \"Make sharing, retention, redaction, and deletion deliberate user choices.\"\n\n**Non-goals** (PRODUCT_INTENT): no deciding which statement is correct/intended; no summarizing/ranking/embedding/interpreting; no agent control or workflow enforcement; no capturing provider-hidden reasoning. \"Those belong to clients such as Turnbridge and Intent Recall, not to this core storage layer.\"\n\n---\n\n## 2. Full roadmap\n\n**README \"Roadmap\" section** (verbatim item names, condensed bodies):\n\n1. **Path-based capture exclusion** — \"the path half of the redaction config ('never record reads of `secrets/**`'); requires correlating `tool_use` file paths with their `tool_result` events.\" Not done.\n2. **Post-push purge** — \"true content removal after the ledger ref has been shared (force-push + collaborator re-fetch coordination); the local pre-push squash shipped with `cledger redact`.\" Not done (only the local pre-push half shipped).\n3. **`re-anchor`** — \"reattach events orphaned by squash merges or history rewrites. The desired end state is that this happens by default: a squash commit should end up carrying the conversations of the branch it squashed. Hard part: squashes often happen off-machine (GitHub 'Squash and merge'), so detection needs patch-id/branch-tip matching after fetch, not a local hook.\" Not done.\n4. **Harness-artifact capture** — \"decide whether the ledger should also preserve valuable non-git-controlled agent artifacts that normally die with a worktree or live outside the repo (e.g. Claude Code auto-memory directories, session state). They fit the `document` kind; the question is scope and capture triggers.\" Not done (open decision).\n5. **Format-drift: re-normalization** — mostly shipped in stages (detection 0.4.0, raw preservation 0.5.0, `cledger renormalize` 0.6.0). \"*Remaining:* this is a manual command — auto-running it after an adapter/version bump on capture is deferred (detecting 'the adapter changed' is its own problem).\"\n6. **Capture/scan redaction feedback loop** — explicitly marked \"*(shipped, 0.6.1 + 0.7.0)*\": masked sync-report output (0.6.1) plus opt-in `knownSecrets` store (0.7.0). \"*Deferred / rejected:* the fuller 'capture-tier is a strict superset of scan-tier' framing was considered and set aside... The value-based learning above is the intended narrow form.\"\n7. **Encrypt the known-secrets store at rest** — \"Owner-only `0600` perms shipped in 0.7.1; the real remaining work is encryption with an OS-keychain-held key (macOS Keychain / libsecret / DPAPI), which must decrypt *non-interactively*.\" Partially done.\n8. **Sub-turn citation anchors** — \"for downstream consumers like intent-recall.\" Not done.\n\n**WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md \"Open questions\"** (overlapping roadmap, near-verbatim):\n- Path-based capture exclusion (layer D's path half).\n- \"Post-push purge tooling (force-push the notes ref + collaborator re-fetch coordination).\"\n- \"Transport currently wires `origin` only; fork workflows (per-remote staging refs, refspecs on other remotes) are unhandled — the pre-push hook does push to whichever remote is being pushed, but fetch staging is origin-scoped.\"\n- Sub-turn citation anchors.\n- \"Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or branch-tip matching after fetch.\"\n- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts as `document` events.\n- \"Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once multiple producers exist.\"\n\n---\n\n## 3. Squash/rebase/remote/sync/mapping specifics — quotes\n\n**Commit-to-conversation mapping (anchoring):**\n- README: events are \"anchored to the commit you were on when the conversation happened. Records ride the commit DAG — merge a branch and its conversations come along.\"\n- TECHNICAL_DESIGN \"Storage\": \"One git note per **anchor commit** under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`.\" And rationale 1: \"**Branch-tied by construction.** Events anchor to `HEAD` at capture time, so conversations ride the commit DAG: merging a branch makes its commits — and therefore their conversations — reachable from the target branch with no sync machinery. `cledger log` scopes to the current branch via `git rev-list` reachability.\"\n- Events also carry `context`: \"repository identity, branch, `HEAD` SHA, cwd, and a dirty-worktree fingerprint (sha256 of `git status --porcelain`).\"\n- Pre-first-commit case: \"Events captured before the first commit exists (unborn `HEAD`) queue in `.git/conversation-ledger/pending.jsonl` and flush into the first real anchor.\"\n\n**Squash merges / orphaned notes** — TECHNICAL_DESIGN, \"### Known limitation: squash merges\" (quoted in full):\n&gt; \"A squash merge discards the source branch's commits, so their conversations remain in the ledger (notes are enumerable regardless of reachability; `cledger log --all` sees them) but drop out of the target branch's reachability view. A future `re-anchor` operation is the intended fix.\"\n\n**Rebases / history rewrites:** never treated separately — always paired with squashes: README roadmap `re-anchor` says \"reattach events orphaned by squash merges or history rewrites\"; Open questions says \"Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default behavior.\"\n\n**GitHub / off-machine squash detection:** README roadmap: \"squashes often happen off-machine (GitHub 'Squash and merge'), so detection needs patch-id/branch-tip matching after fetch, not a local hook.\" Open questions: \"requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or branch-tip matching after fetch.\"\n\n**PR flows:** No document mentions pull requests explicitly; GitHub appears only via \"Squash and merge\" and the fork-workflow gap (\"fork workflows (per-remote staging refs, refspecs on other remotes) are unhandled\").\n\n**Commit rewriting (of the notes ref, by redaction):** `cledger redact` \"squashes local notes history so prior content is unrecoverable (pre-push only; post-push purge tooling is planned, not yet built)\" (README). TECHNICAL_DESIGN: \"rewrites the note line and appends a companion `redaction` event with `links.redacts`, then squashes the local notes ref so the prior blob is unreachable — honest history without secret retention.\"\n\n**Sync semantics** — README \"Sharing (transport)\" and TECHNICAL_DESIGN \"Transport\":\n- Push: \"A `pre-push` hook calls `cledger transport-push &lt;remote&gt;`, which pushes the ledger ref gated by the layer-E scan. Policy: a finding holds back *only the ledger* — secrets never leave the machine, but a false positive never blocks shipping code; `{\"transport\": {\"strict\": true}}` escalates to aborting the entire push.\" Hook install is chain-safe, backs off under `core.hooksPath`/husky, and a `CLEDGER_INTERNAL` guard prevents re-triggering.\n- Fetch: \"A `+refs/notes/conversation-ledger:refs/notes/cledger-incoming` refspec on `origin` makes plain `git fetch`/`git pull` stage the remote's ref; `absorbIncoming` folds the staging ref into the local ref lazily at read time (every `readEvents`) via the same `cat_sort_uniq` union — absorption can only add events, and the local ref is never force-overwritten.\"\n- Merge model: \"Conflict-free concurrency. Deterministic serialization + sorted unique lines mean git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes merge strategy... unions concurrent appends cleanly — the same mechanism git-bug and git-appraise rely on.\"\n- `cledger sync` \"remains the explicit path and the fallback when hooks are declined\"; opt-out via `{\"transport\": {\"hook\": false, \"fetchRefspec\": false}}`.\n\n**Post-push purge:** three mentions. README roadmap (quoted in section 2 above); README redact command (\"post-push purge tooling is planned, not yet built\"); TECHNICAL_DESIGN: \"Post-push purge (force-push + collaborator coordination) is deliberately separate, deferred tooling\" and Open questions: \"Post-push purge tooling (force-push the notes ref + collaborator re-fetch coordination).\"\n\n---\n\n## 4. \"Privacy and integrity\" (WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md) — summary\n\n- **Threat model:** trust boundary is transport — transcripts are already plaintext locally, so redaction protects the shared record. Once a secret reaches a note removal is expensive (notes ref history retains prior blobs), so prevention runs at capture with a last checkpoint at sync. Event ids double as content hashes making mutation detectable.\n- **Six layers (A–F):** A — capture-time pattern redaction, default on, deliberately conservative (\"capture-tier rules must be near-zero-false-positive by construction\" because a false positive \"silently rewrites the record, which violates the preservation commitment\"); runs before ids are computed on both `content` and `raw.data`. B — gitleaks/trufflehog used only as test oracles, never at runtime. C — opt-in env-value masking (machine-dependent, id churn accepted). D — user pattern regexes from config; path-based exclusion planned, not in v1. E — sync-time scan of only new events, tiered; noisy rules allowed \"precisely because they only warn a human — they never rewrite anything\"; findings block the ledger push with a report whose matched span is fully masked so \"a captured report cannot re-seed the finding it describes\"; remediation via allowlist or `cledger redact`; paranoid entropy tier opt-in. F — opt-in known-secret learning: values a `cledger redact --pattern` scrubbed are stored plaintext, `0600`, in `.git/conversation-ledger/known-secrets.json` and exact-matched out of all future captures; sub-8-char values dropped; id churn accepted.\n- **Redaction metadata:** placeholder `[REDACTED:&lt;rule-id&gt;:&lt;fingerprint&gt;]` with truncated sha256 fingerprint so identical secrets correlate without being recoverable; a `redactions` array sits outside the identity subset. Determinism rule: \"capture-tier redaction must be a pure function of source content + versioned ruleset, or rescans duplicate events.\" Human redaction of an existing event rewrites the note line, appends a companion `redaction` event, and squashes the local notes ref; post-push purge is deferred.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Design principles constraining a squash-merge/re-anchor solution\n\nAny fix for \"notes attached to commits that GitHub squash-merges orphan\" is boxed in by:\n\n1. **Never touch the working tree / git status** — README: records \"never touch your working tree or `git status`\"; PRODUCT_INTENT: \"Keep storage out of ordinary working-tree status views.\"\n2. **Append-only, no silent rewrites** — \"do not silently rewrite history\" (PRODUCT_INTENT); redaction/supersession model shows the sanctioned pattern: never delete, append a companion event with `links` (`redacts`, `supersedes`). Re-anchoring would presumably need the same append-plus-link shape rather than moving/rewriting notes.\n3. **Content-addressed, deterministic ids** — id = hash of the identity subset; anything changing identity fields churns ids and breaks dedup. Notably `context` (branch/HEAD) is *outside* the identity subset (it's \"volatile provenance\"), and `links` is *inside* it — relevant to how a re-anchor event could be modeled.\n4. **GC-safe, everything inside git** — \"All content lives inline in the note blob, reachable from the ref. No orphan data branches, no pointers to stores outside the repository.\" (Though note the squash-limitation passage says notes are enumerable regardless of commit reachability, so orphaned anchors aren't GC'd data — just invisible to branch-scoped views.)\n5. **Conflict-free concurrency** — any solution must survive `cat_sort_uniq` union merging (deterministic serialization, sorted unique lines) across machines.\n6. **Local state under `.git/conversation-ledger/` is \"local, rebuildable state — never the record of truth\"** — detection caches/cursors can live there but the re-anchor record itself must be in the notes ref.\n7. **Detection must be fetch-side, not hook-side** — the docs pre-commit to a mechanism: \"detection needs patch-id/branch-tip matching after fetch, not a local hook\" (squashes happen on GitHub's servers). Desired end state is that this is *default* behavior: \"a squash commit should end up carrying the conversations of the branch it squashed.\"\n8. **Hooks never fail the user's session; transport never blocks code** — capture hooks \"no-op silently outside git repositories, never fail the user's session\"; `ensureTransport` \"never throws\"; a ledger problem must not block a code push (non-strict default). A re-anchor pass running inside fetch/read paths would inherit these constraints.\n9. **No interpretation** — the ledger \"never summarizes, ranks, or interprets\"; re-anchoring must be a mechanical provenance operation (patch-id/tip matching), not a judgment about which conversation \"belongs\" to which change.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>29083</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>3</tool_uses><duration_ms>61027</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>","type":"text"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"1ddda1003ecda2e4821a3ee684226d0fa0fc9932","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3","seq":32},"id":"ev1-6037d57926f01596b28ee02ba179305f5dff351b25d0712ad6541713ffb43777","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-21T05:19:18.478Z","producer":{"session_id":"4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.7.1"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":"<task-notification>\n<task-id>a96e6e1ccd9c26d11</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01HPMEg3vabFCEET6A2yvQ5V</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-evintunador-repos-evintunador-conversation-ledger/4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3/tasks/a96e6e1ccd9c26d11.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Summarize docs and roadmap\" finished</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent stops with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result># Report: conversation-ledger docs review\n\nSources read: `/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/README.md`, `/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md`, `/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md`\n\n---\n\n## 1. Product intent and core guarantees\n\n**README intro:** \"Durable, attributable records of visible coding-agent conversations, stored in your repository as git notes.\" It \"appends immutable JSONL evidence events to `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`, anchored to the commit you were on when the conversation happened. Records ride the commit DAG — merge a branch and its conversations come along — never touch your working tree or `git status`.\" And: \"The ledger itself never summarizes, ranks, or interprets. It stores what was visibly said, by whom, against which commit — nothing more.\"\n\n**PRODUCT_INTENT.md \"Purpose\":** \"Conversation Ledger preserves durable, inspectable records of visible conversations between people and coding agents. It is a general conversation provenance primitive, not an intent-analysis product. Downstream consumers may use its records as evidence about why a repository changed, but the ledger must not impose that interpretation.\" The record must remain useful beyond a single tool: \"cross-CLI continuity, archival/export, code attribution, review, and later intent retrieval are all valid independent uses.\"\n\n**\"Auditable history\" here means:**\n- Events are immutable and content-addressed: `id` is `ev1-` + sha256 of the identity subset, so \"capture is idempotent by construction, and the id doubles as the content hash that makes mutation detectable\" (TECHNICAL_DESIGN, \"Canonical objects\").\n- \"Redaction appends a `redaction` event rather than silently rewriting history\" (README, \"Storage model\"); TECHNICAL_DESIGN calls this \"honest history without secret retention.\"\n- Behavioral commitments (PRODUCT_INTENT): \"Preserve source material and provenance; do not silently rewrite history\"; \"Preserve exact visible turns before creating optional derived views\"; record \"repository, branch, commit, worktree state, author, timestamps, and capture mechanism with each artifact whenever available\"; \"Keep storage out of ordinary working-tree status views while retaining normal Git durability and shareability\"; \"Make sharing, retention, redaction, and deletion deliberate user choices.\"\n\n**Non-goals** (PRODUCT_INTENT): no deciding which statement is correct/intended; no summarizing/ranking/embedding/interpreting; no agent control or workflow enforcement; no capturing provider-hidden reasoning. \"Those belong to clients such as Turnbridge and Intent Recall, not to this core storage layer.\"\n\n---\n\n## 2. Full roadmap\n\n**README \"Roadmap\" section** (verbatim item names, condensed bodies):\n\n1. **Path-based capture exclusion** — \"the path half of the redaction config ('never record reads of `secrets/**`'); requires correlating `tool_use` file paths with their `tool_result` events.\" Not done.\n2. **Post-push purge** — \"true content removal after the ledger ref has been shared (force-push + collaborator re-fetch coordination); the local pre-push squash shipped with `cledger redact`.\" Not done (only the local pre-push half shipped).\n3. **`re-anchor`** — \"reattach events orphaned by squash merges or history rewrites. The desired end state is that this happens by default: a squash commit should end up carrying the conversations of the branch it squashed. Hard part: squashes often happen off-machine (GitHub 'Squash and merge'), so detection needs patch-id/branch-tip matching after fetch, not a local hook.\" Not done.\n4. **Harness-artifact capture** — \"decide whether the ledger should also preserve valuable non-git-controlled agent artifacts that normally die with a worktree or live outside the repo (e.g. Claude Code auto-memory directories, session state). They fit the `document` kind; the question is scope and capture triggers.\" Not done (open decision).\n5. **Format-drift: re-normalization** — mostly shipped in stages (detection 0.4.0, raw preservation 0.5.0, `cledger renormalize` 0.6.0). \"*Remaining:* this is a manual command — auto-running it after an adapter/version bump on capture is deferred (detecting 'the adapter changed' is its own problem).\"\n6. **Capture/s